WEBVTT

00:00:26.744 --> 00:00:31.385
<v Ahmed Kabir Chaion>Hello everyone. Welcome once again
to WordPress Accessibility Day 2020.

00:00:31.410 --> 00:00:33.079
My name is Ahmed Kabir Chaion

00:00:33.159 --> 00:00:36.038
and I'm working as a business
development manager at WeDevs.

00:00:36.063 --> 00:00:39.659
I'm also a regular contributor to the
making WordPress documentation,

00:00:39.684 --> 00:00:44.640
design, polyglots, accessibility,
hosting community, Learn WordPress

00:00:44.665 --> 00:00:45.767
and marketing team.

00:00:45.792 --> 00:00:48.307
I will be your host for this session.

00:00:48.386 --> 00:00:52.948
You're here for the 8 a.m. UTC talk
with Hidde de Vries.

00:00:52.973 --> 00:00:55.757
Please feel free to add your
questions to the YouTube chat,

00:00:55.782 --> 00:00:57.433
and we'll answer those at the end.

00:00:58.282 --> 00:01:02.000
Your content management
system plays a decisive part

00:01:02.024 --> 00:01:03.759
in creating accessible content.

00:01:04.280 --> 00:01:09.188
Suggest the authoring tools
accessibility guideline—ATAG.

00:01:09.498 --> 00:01:11.871
Whenever a content
designer creates content,

00:01:11.896 --> 00:01:15.799
the CMS could help with the
accessibility of it.

00:01:16.159 --> 00:01:19.120
For instance, when a designer
drops in an image,

00:01:19.400 --> 00:01:22.439
the CMS could point to the ideal
text alternative

00:01:22.670 --> 00:01:25.359
or calculate the consequences
for color contrast.

00:01:25.840 --> 00:01:29.938
In this talk, you will learn
more about what ATAG is,

00:01:30.288 --> 00:01:32.192
and how with ATAG in mind,

00:01:32.217 --> 00:01:38.145
CMSs can personally assist content editors
on their way to a more accessible website.

00:01:39.549 --> 00:01:44.600
The speaker for this talk, Hidde, is a
web developer and accessibility specialist

00:01:44.625 --> 00:01:48.842
at the W3C's Web
Accessibility Initiative or WAI.

00:01:49.497 --> 00:01:53.651
Based in Rotterdam, Netherlands,
as part of the WAI guide project,

00:01:53.676 --> 00:01:56.516
he works on the
accessibility of authoring tools

00:01:56.541 --> 00:01:59.414
like CMSs and website creators,

00:01:59.439 --> 00:02:04.560
and guidance that supports the Web
Content Accessibility Guidelines, WCAG.

00:02:04.585 --> 00:02:07.355
He has over 10 years of experience

00:02:07.380 --> 00:02:11.500
working as a freelance front-end
developer and accessibility person

00:02:11.525 --> 00:02:14.908
for organizations like Mozilla
and the Dutch government.

00:02:14.933 --> 00:02:17.441
On his blog, he writes regularly about

00:02:17.466 --> 00:02:20.879
reusable components, CSS and
web accessibility,

00:02:21.240 --> 00:02:25.216
which brings to the session, your
CMS is an accessibility assistant.

00:02:25.613 --> 00:02:26.680
Take it away, Hidde.

00:02:41.802 --> 00:02:45.096
<v Hidde de Vries>Hello, this is Hidde
and I'm here today to talk about

00:02:45.120 --> 00:02:48.516
how your CMS could be seen
as an accessibility assistant

00:02:48.541 --> 00:02:50.240
and how that can help organizations

00:02:50.265 --> 00:02:54.671
including maybe the
clients or users of a CMS.

00:02:55.410 --> 00:02:56.755
Very briefly about myself,

00:02:56.779 --> 00:03:01.862
I work as an accessibility specialist at
the W3C, the World Wide Web Consortium,

00:03:02.346 --> 00:03:05.215
where I worked at the
Web Accessibility Initiative.

00:03:05.949 --> 00:03:09.139
We have a website which I'd like to plug.

00:03:09.164 --> 00:03:12.076
On our website, there's loads of
information about web accessibility,

00:03:12.101 --> 00:03:15.956
about planning, designing,
developing, testing,

00:03:15.981 --> 00:03:19.339
advocating and training for.

00:03:20.021 --> 00:03:24.790
So many people don't know about all these
amazing resources that are on this website.

00:03:25.294 --> 00:03:27.247
So I thought I'd mention it.

00:03:27.271 --> 00:03:30.898
But disclaimer, I do work on
some of the content for this site.

00:03:30.923 --> 00:03:35.685
Now, I focus mostly in
my work on authoring tools

00:03:35.710 --> 00:03:39.757
and authoring tools, if you're
not familiar with that phrase,

00:03:39.782 --> 00:03:42.706
they are tools that create web content.

00:03:42.730 --> 00:03:46.151
And with that,
as probably won't surprise you,

00:03:46.176 --> 00:03:50.589
they are also tools that can improve
a lot of web accessibility at once.

00:03:50.614 --> 00:03:52.636
That is a very exciting prospect, I think.

00:03:52.661 --> 00:03:56.452
And I'll be talking a lot today about
how we can make that a reality.

00:03:56.477 --> 00:04:01.831
How can we really employ
authoring tools to improve accessibility

00:04:01.856 --> 00:04:03.719
in many places at once?

00:04:04.871 --> 00:04:08.100
Now, first, let's look at a couple
of examples of authoring tools.

00:04:08.125 --> 00:04:11.869
We're talking about things like
WYSIWYG editors, course creators,

00:04:11.894 --> 00:04:16.000
learning management systems, or
anything that they use in online education—

00:04:16.025 --> 00:04:18.534
very important in times of COVID.

00:04:19.085 --> 00:04:21.248
Content management systems, of course,

00:04:21.684 --> 00:04:25.240
Wikipedia, your "save
as HTML" functionality,

00:04:25.265 --> 00:04:28.931
social media, form
generators, site builders,

00:04:28.956 --> 00:04:34.029
lots of these different things all have in
common that they create content for the web

00:04:34.054 --> 00:04:36.894
or that they provide some sort of interface

00:04:36.919 --> 00:04:41.246
for their users to create something
that will ultimately live on the web.

00:04:42.238 --> 00:04:46.285
Now, specifically about CMS,
as we're at WordPress Accessibility Day,

00:04:46.310 --> 00:04:49.858
you can think of the
authoring tool as the CMS itself.

00:04:49.883 --> 00:04:55.058
And I imagine some people watching
this today work on WordPress Core

00:04:55.083 --> 00:04:57.396
or have provided some patches for it

00:04:57.421 --> 00:05:00.360
or maybe considering
contributing to WordPress.

00:05:00.385 --> 00:05:06.122
But others may be working on plugins like
form builders, custom field managing stuff,

00:05:06.147 --> 00:05:10.245
things where you can manage events
or social media, cookie banners, even

00:05:10.270 --> 00:05:12.888
just anything that you
can plug into a website,

00:05:12.913 --> 00:05:14.802
and that will also create web content,

00:05:14.827 --> 00:05:17.040
it will also be considered
as an authoring tool.

00:05:17.065 --> 00:05:19.223
And when I talk about CMSs in this talk,

00:05:19.247 --> 00:05:23.319
I very much also mean
plugins and themes as well.

00:05:25.311 --> 00:05:28.624
Now, the web is meant to work for everyone.

00:05:28.649 --> 00:05:32.680
That is a point that we take
very seriously at the W3C.

00:05:33.000 --> 00:05:37.274
This is a photograph of Sir Tim
Berners-Lee, the inventor of the web

00:05:37.299 --> 00:05:42.425
who was at the opening ceremony
of the London Olympics in 2012.

00:05:42.480 --> 00:05:46.026
And he made these four words appear:
This is for everyone.

00:05:46.051 --> 00:05:51.374
Now, I think, and I haven't
checked this with him personally,

00:05:51.399 --> 00:05:54.839
but I think you could
interpret this in various ways.

00:05:55.273 --> 00:06:02.812
One is that the web should be
available for everyone to get onto the web.

00:06:02.837 --> 00:06:05.656
So, of course, you need
to get a cable subscription

00:06:05.681 --> 00:06:08.609
or go to a library and
maybe pay to use a computer.

00:06:08.634 --> 00:06:13.093
But ultimately, the web is available
for everyone. This is for everyone.

00:06:13.974 --> 00:06:18.070
Secondly, I think everyone can
have a website on the web as well.

00:06:18.104 --> 00:06:21.491
You don't need to apply for
permit at your local government

00:06:21.516 --> 00:06:25.439
or something like that or, you
know, do something very special.

00:06:25.920 --> 00:06:28.397
You need to have a
web server or rent one.

00:06:28.421 --> 00:06:31.765
You can put some HTML on there
and make it available on the URL.

00:06:31.790 --> 00:06:34.784
So in that sense, it's also for everyone.

00:06:34.809 --> 00:06:38.383
And the third way that you could
read this—this is for everyone—

00:06:38.407 --> 00:06:41.942
is as this is something
that should work for everyone,

00:06:41.967 --> 00:06:43.879
including people with disabilities.

00:06:43.904 --> 00:06:48.093
That is the definition that we use at WAI—

00:06:48.118 --> 00:06:50.647
Making the web work
for people with disabilities

00:06:50.671 --> 00:06:53.575
is what Web Accessibility is about.

00:06:53.600 --> 00:06:57.422
We want to make sure that this
is for everyone.

00:06:57.914 --> 00:07:01.223
Now, to that extent, at WAI,
we have three web standards

00:07:01.248 --> 00:07:05.747
that are about the accessibility
of web content ultimately.

00:07:06.000 --> 00:07:08.920
Now, many people will be familiar
with the WCAG standard,

00:07:09.095 --> 00:07:12.399
which stands for the Web Content
Accessibility Guidelines.

00:07:12.682 --> 00:07:16.299
But there's two more sets of
guidelines that are very closely related

00:07:16.324 --> 00:07:20.839
and that together really create
that picture of an accessible web.

00:07:21.319 --> 00:07:25.983
So there is the Web Content Accessibility
Guidelines about web content itself.

00:07:26.040 --> 00:07:30.650
But what about the software
that people use to access web content?

00:07:30.713 --> 00:07:32.639
Browsers or user agents?

00:07:32.639 --> 00:07:34.551
There's a specific standard for that,

00:07:34.575 --> 00:07:37.680
the User Agent Accessibility
Guidelines, UAAG.

00:07:38.592 --> 00:07:41.965
And what about the software that creates
web content, authoring tools?

00:07:42.160 --> 00:07:45.279
And for that, we have the Authoring Tools
Accessibility Guidelines.

00:07:45.480 --> 00:07:48.416
So together, these three
standards, they all say something

00:07:48.441 --> 00:07:51.025
about the accessibility of web content,

00:07:51.050 --> 00:07:52.447
about the content itself,

00:07:52.472 --> 00:07:54.920
about the software we use
to view the content,

00:07:54.959 --> 00:07:58.720
and about the software we use
to create the content.

00:07:59.639 --> 00:08:03.600
Now, authoring tools are very important
and CMSs with that.

00:08:03.600 --> 00:08:06.360
They're essential in this picture
of web accessibility

00:08:06.618 --> 00:08:09.959
because if we get it right, if we get
it right in Authoring Tools,

00:08:10.000 --> 00:08:12.040
we'll be able to include more
content creators.

00:08:12.040 --> 00:08:14.399
We can have more people publish
stuff on the web.

00:08:15.393 --> 00:08:16.556
And the second reason

00:08:16.581 --> 00:08:19.917
that I think Authoring Tools
are so important and exciting

00:08:19.942 --> 00:08:24.329
is that content creators may be
allowed to fix accessibility problems

00:08:24.354 --> 00:08:26.215
before their website goes live.

00:08:26.240 --> 00:08:29.686
It is the central theme of what
I want to say today.

00:08:31.860 --> 00:08:35.494
Now, the standard for
authoring tools, as I said, is ATAG

00:08:35.519 --> 00:08:38.480
with the latest iteration, ATAG 2.0.

00:08:38.930 --> 00:08:43.111
Now, in ATAG, and I'll talk
about a lot of ATAG today,

00:08:43.136 --> 00:08:46.415
but if you want to read
it at your own pace,

00:08:46.440 --> 00:08:48.785
you can visit the source
called ATAG at a glance.

00:08:48.810 --> 00:08:53.399
It's a page that has a bulleted list of the
main points that are in the ATAG standard.

00:08:53.679 --> 00:08:56.045
So that is something you could
review at your own pace.

00:08:56.069 --> 00:09:00.844
But today we'll also go through a bunch
of different guidelines that are in ATAG,

00:09:00.869 --> 00:09:02.972
success criteria,

00:09:03.014 --> 00:09:08.065
and I hope to give you a good
overview of what you can find in ATAG

00:09:08.090 --> 00:09:13.000
and how it can really help end users
and people who edit content on the web.

00:09:14.600 --> 00:09:16.759
Now, the ATAG standard consists
of two parts.

00:09:16.960 --> 00:09:19.519
The first part is about the
editing experience.

00:09:19.519 --> 00:09:24.206
So the content editing itself,
the backend, so to say.

00:09:24.618 --> 00:09:27.320
And the second part is about
the output of content.

00:09:27.759 --> 00:09:30.265
I'll focus mostly on output today,

00:09:30.290 --> 00:09:34.698
but also talk a bit about what we can
do to improve the editing experience

00:09:34.722 --> 00:09:36.279
for people with disabilities.

00:09:37.660 --> 00:09:38.922
Yeah, let's look at that first.

00:09:38.947 --> 00:09:43.919
So part A of ATAG is about the
accessibility of the editing experience.

00:09:44.159 --> 00:09:47.881
So the very first
success criterion A 1.1.1

00:09:47.906 --> 00:09:52.120
is about making sure that your
interface conforms to the WCAG standard.

00:09:52.399 --> 00:09:56.279
And part of that, of course, is making sure
that your interface works with text zoom.

00:09:56.304 --> 00:10:00.577
It's something I heard a lot from users
when I talk to them for my work,

00:10:00.943 --> 00:10:03.101
is when they zoom in the interface,

00:10:04.046 --> 00:10:06.107
It's not as easy for them
to use the interface

00:10:06.132 --> 00:10:09.360
or sometimes the interface becomes
completely unusable.

00:10:09.631 --> 00:10:11.880
So testing with text zoom
is one thing you can do.

00:10:11.904 --> 00:10:13.425
Text alternatives for icons.

00:10:13.449 --> 00:10:17.870
It's very common these days to have
interfaces that consist of just icons.

00:10:18.080 --> 00:10:22.559
So if you work on a plugin or a theme or
something that has an editing interface

00:10:22.559 --> 00:10:25.106
where icons are the
main thing you click on,

00:10:25.131 --> 00:10:27.177
make sure that there are
text alternatives for them

00:10:27.202 --> 00:10:30.240
so that there's an accessible
name somewhere in the source code.

00:10:31.080 --> 00:10:34.960
Make it work with a keyboard is
another great advice.

00:10:35.494 --> 00:10:37.501
And that includes things like visible focus

00:10:37.526 --> 00:10:40.289
so that you can see at all times
where you are on the page

00:10:40.313 --> 00:10:41.720
before you interact with something.

00:10:42.055 --> 00:10:43.777
And that you can use all controls.

00:10:43.802 --> 00:10:47.240
So that includes all form
fields, anchors and buttons.

00:10:47.399 --> 00:10:52.402
Another recommendation in ATAG is about
displaying previews accessibly.

00:10:52.639 --> 00:10:56.323
Because most content management
systems or authoring tools in general,

00:10:56.348 --> 00:11:00.720
plugins as well, will have some way to
preview the content that you're working on.

00:11:01.039 --> 00:11:06.519
And this criterion is about making sure
that that content is accessible as well.

00:11:07.200 --> 00:11:09.519
Or you can think of things like
helping with spelling.

00:11:10.039 --> 00:11:12.779
Some people may have dyslexia and they're
editing some content.

00:11:12.804 --> 00:11:16.652
You can help them a great deal by helping
them correct their spelling.

00:11:18.152 --> 00:11:21.801
Now that's a bit about the first part of
ATAG, improving the editing experience.

00:11:21.826 --> 00:11:23.799
What I really promised to
talk about today is

00:11:23.799 --> 00:11:27.120
how your CMS could be an accessibility
assistant.

00:11:27.480 --> 00:11:31.282
And in that sense, support the
production of accessible content

00:11:31.307 --> 00:11:34.440
as the official name
is for part B of ATAG.

00:11:35.180 --> 00:11:39.200
And for that, let's talk a bit about
what accessible content is.

00:11:39.488 --> 00:11:42.002
It is things like: that you
have tables with headers,

00:11:42.027 --> 00:11:44.320
that you have forms with
the appropriate labels,

00:11:44.519 --> 00:11:48.440
that you have hero images with plenty of
contrast, that videos are captioned,

00:11:48.840 --> 00:11:52.279
that you can have multilingual content
with the right language attributes,

00:11:52.879 --> 00:11:55.494
that everything is nested
according to specification,

00:11:55.519 --> 00:11:57.193
that carousels can pause,

00:11:57.218 --> 00:11:59.055
and that you have
sensible heading structures.

00:11:59.080 --> 00:12:03.159
So all of these things, they contribute
to more accessible content.

00:12:03.360 --> 00:12:06.114
So for your end users,
for the people using the website

00:12:06.139 --> 00:12:08.720
or, you know, web content
that you're creating,

00:12:09.242 --> 00:12:11.178
all of these things need to be in order.

00:12:11.440 --> 00:12:14.360
So if we want to have a good
accessibility assistant,

00:12:14.385 --> 00:12:16.440
it should assist with all of
these different things.

00:12:16.799 --> 00:12:20.519
And usually they could be different
products, right?

00:12:20.519 --> 00:12:24.680
Because sometimes you might have
a plugin specifically for creating tables

00:12:24.705 --> 00:12:27.600
or one specifically for creating forms.

00:12:27.799 --> 00:12:32.053
So they could be specialized products
that focus on these specific tasks.

00:12:33.191 --> 00:12:35.283
And an accessibility
assistant would of course

00:12:35.308 --> 00:12:37.473
help avoid inaccessible content.

00:12:37.498 --> 00:12:40.039
So it would avoid things
like tables with no headers.

00:12:40.240 --> 00:12:42.923
It would avoid things like
form fields that have no names,

00:12:42.948 --> 00:12:45.600
illegible text, captionless videos,

00:12:45.799 --> 00:12:49.319
multilingual content that doesn't
have the right language attributes,

00:12:49.344 --> 00:12:51.568
non-standard nesting,

00:12:51.799 --> 00:12:55.473
carousels that don't have a pause button
and headings for the wrong reasons.

00:12:55.519 --> 00:12:59.787
So a CMS that really helps
you get your accessibility right

00:12:59.812 --> 00:13:03.192
will maybe warn you for
these kinds of mistakes

00:13:03.217 --> 00:13:06.303
or it will generate markup that
doesn't have these problems

00:13:06.328 --> 00:13:11.080
and provide templates that
comes with the right stuff.

00:13:11.984 --> 00:13:13.360
So that's what this is all about.

00:13:13.360 --> 00:13:18.240
We want to avoid inaccessible content
for our end users ultimately.

00:13:18.559 --> 00:13:21.676
And we want to help the people
that are using our products

00:13:21.701 --> 00:13:24.487
like our CMS or our plugin or our theme.

00:13:24.815 --> 00:13:27.154
We want to help them avoid
inaccessible content

00:13:27.179 --> 00:13:30.200
so that they can ship a website
that is accessible

00:13:30.773 --> 00:13:35.134
and find problems before they
ship it ideally.

00:13:35.159 --> 00:13:37.506
So a great CMS can really
help content managers

00:13:37.530 --> 00:13:39.639
make their content more accessible.

00:13:40.600 --> 00:13:44.840
Think about things like when content
is created, it is accessible,

00:13:44.879 --> 00:13:50.682
which is the success criteria on 1.1.2,
B1.1.2 in the ATAG standard.

00:13:50.896 --> 00:13:52.799
And that is about things like, you know,

00:13:52.824 --> 00:13:55.545
you need to make sure that it's
nested according to the standard.

00:13:55.879 --> 00:13:59.879
You want to make sure there's no empty
links inside of this content.

00:14:00.240 --> 00:14:03.919
Sometimes to make content accessible,
you need some more information.

00:14:03.919 --> 00:14:07.590
So maybe you need to prompt the
user for required accessibility information

00:14:07.615 --> 00:14:09.894
like a caption for a table,

00:14:09.919 --> 00:14:12.919
an alternative text for an
image or for video.

00:14:13.383 --> 00:14:16.589
So those sorts of things
you need to prompt for

00:14:16.614 --> 00:14:19.200
if you know that that could
cause an accessibility problem

00:14:19.200 --> 00:14:23.396
and, you know, you rely on the
content editor to provide the information,

00:14:23.421 --> 00:14:24.854
you'll need to prompt for it.

00:14:24.879 --> 00:14:29.111
So captions for tables, alt text for images
and labels for form fields

00:14:29.136 --> 00:14:32.054
are just some examples of
things that you could prompt for.

00:14:32.720 --> 00:14:36.679
Or when content is generated, maybe there
could be automated accessibility checks.

00:14:36.871 --> 00:14:39.212
Or if it can only be checked manually,

00:14:39.245 --> 00:14:43.639
maybe the tools should suggest
to the user to do a manual check.

00:14:43.879 --> 00:14:47.360
For instance, if it's about the
heading structure of the page,

00:14:47.385 --> 00:14:50.360
or if it is about text alternatives,

00:14:50.360 --> 00:14:52.721
maybe they are centrally managed

00:14:52.745 --> 00:14:56.342
and you want the user to make sure
that the text alternative makes sense

00:14:56.367 --> 00:14:58.082
for this specific use case.

00:14:58.107 --> 00:15:00.286
For instance, a photo of a speaker,

00:15:00.310 --> 00:15:02.159
but their name is also in the content.

00:15:02.159 --> 00:15:04.710
So maybe at that point
you would want a zero

00:15:04.734 --> 00:15:08.395
or you would want an
empty alternative text

00:15:08.420 --> 00:15:10.759
rather than repeat the
name of the speaker.

00:15:10.759 --> 00:15:13.179
So that sort of thing that
requires a manual check,

00:15:13.204 --> 00:15:17.000
someone who knows the content
and understands it to go through it.

00:15:17.000 --> 00:15:19.496
And as an authoring tool, as a CMS,

00:15:19.520 --> 00:15:21.923
you could actually
provide the right instructions

00:15:21.948 --> 00:15:26.813
and help the user to figure out
how to make their content accessible.

00:15:28.790 --> 00:15:32.600
2.1.1 is about allowing to create
accessible content.

00:15:32.940 --> 00:15:36.480
So not everyone realizes this, but there
are a lot of authoring tools out there

00:15:36.480 --> 00:15:41.559
that don't provide or don't allow for
entering accessible content.

00:15:41.559 --> 00:15:44.730
For instance, if you upload a video,

00:15:44.754 --> 00:15:47.095
if there's no caption,
it isn't accessible.

00:15:47.120 --> 00:15:50.279
But if your video widget
doesn't have a caption button,

00:15:50.304 --> 00:15:55.900
then the user cannot create an
accessible video with your authoring tool

00:15:55.924 --> 00:15:58.559
or if there's no alternative
text option.

00:15:58.559 --> 00:16:00.146
And some social media, for instance,

00:16:00.171 --> 00:16:03.080
only recently added the
option to add alternative text.

00:16:03.080 --> 00:16:05.008
And there is a bunch
of social media out there

00:16:05.033 --> 00:16:07.639
that still don't have
that option available.

00:16:07.919 --> 00:16:10.359
So even if users want to
create accessible content,

00:16:10.384 --> 00:16:13.531
they are not able to because
there's no option for alternative text.

00:16:14.341 --> 00:16:17.428
So for image fields, that means
there should be an alternative text field

00:16:17.453 --> 00:16:21.519
and for video players, there should
be an upload button for captions.

00:16:21.919 --> 00:16:25.647
And this is specifically important
for those creating plugins

00:16:25.672 --> 00:16:27.823
that deal with video or images.

00:16:27.848 --> 00:16:30.282
make sure that people can
manage their alternative text

00:16:30.307 --> 00:16:33.985
so that they can create
accessible content in the first place.

00:16:35.667 --> 00:16:39.326
Something else that ATAG recommends
is to have accessible templates

00:16:39.359 --> 00:16:41.182
for the most common use cases

00:16:41.206 --> 00:16:43.360
and to be able to filter for that.

00:16:45.320 --> 00:16:49.559
I know there is a filter available in the
WordPress directory of different themes.

00:16:49.951 --> 00:16:51.671
So that is another important way

00:16:51.705 --> 00:16:54.679
that you can help content
editors make the right decisions.

00:16:55.279 --> 00:17:00.750
And there's B2.5.1, which says that you
should provide accessible UI components

00:17:00.775 --> 00:17:03.919
or as the specification calls it—
pre-authored content.

00:17:04.160 --> 00:17:08.645
So when you provide something
like a carousel or tabs component

00:17:08.670 --> 00:17:11.562
and users can add that into the page,

00:17:11.586 --> 00:17:13.913
make sure that they
are accessible by default

00:17:13.938 --> 00:17:17.317
so that the content editor
doesn't need to do anything.

00:17:17.400 --> 00:17:19.720
It just ships as an accessible component.

00:17:20.079 --> 00:17:23.158
So it makes a lot of sense
to spend time on accessibility

00:17:23.183 --> 00:17:26.829
if you provide something
like a carousel tool,

00:17:26.853 --> 00:17:30.029
because everyone who is
going to use your plugin

00:17:30.054 --> 00:17:32.079
is going to have a
more accessible website.

00:17:32.079 --> 00:17:38.465
So it's going to have a huge effect
if you spend an extra time on accessibility

00:17:38.490 --> 00:17:40.746
for all of those end users specifically.

00:17:41.675 --> 00:17:46.706
Now here's some
interpretation of B3.1.1, which is,

00:17:46.731 --> 00:17:49.680
why not warn users when they
introduce a color contrast issue.

00:17:50.079 --> 00:17:53.911
Say you work at an agency and a
designer has produced this beautiful header

00:17:53.936 --> 00:17:57.400
with a dark photo of a black
cat with white text on top of it.

00:17:57.919 --> 00:17:59.252
It has perfect contrast

00:17:59.277 --> 00:18:02.353
and it's been checked according
to the accessibility guidelines.

00:18:02.378 --> 00:18:04.994
This is good, it passes all the tests,

00:18:05.018 --> 00:18:07.542
but then someone
decides to replace the photo

00:18:07.567 --> 00:18:10.150
with one of Korean food in this case,

00:18:10.174 --> 00:18:13.424
and it is a perfectly valid photo,

00:18:13.449 --> 00:18:15.678
but it is very light and
the text is also light.

00:18:15.703 --> 00:18:18.151
So at this point, when
we drop in this photo,

00:18:18.176 --> 00:18:20.366
we've introduced a color contrast issue.

00:18:20.962 --> 00:18:24.480
Now it's possible to programmatically
detect color contrast problems.

00:18:24.756 --> 00:18:27.991
And with that, you could provide
a warning for the content author

00:18:28.016 --> 00:18:29.817
that something is going wrong here.

00:18:30.008 --> 00:18:31.960
You could say, well,
there's not enough contrast.

00:18:31.960 --> 00:18:34.079
Maybe there should
be a background color

00:18:34.104 --> 00:18:36.680
painted behind this text
to fix the problem.

00:18:37.039 --> 00:18:39.647
Or in some cases, a
larger text or bolder font

00:18:39.672 --> 00:18:42.244
could be just enough to
address the problem.

00:18:43.400 --> 00:18:46.640
Something else that you could do is to add
a spell checker to content fields.

00:18:46.972 --> 00:18:53.799
I have a button here that says "Swbmit",
which I guess for visual sighted users,

00:18:54.039 --> 00:18:57.136
they might parse that in their head
and see that it probably says submit

00:18:57.161 --> 00:18:59.359
because the W looks so much like a U.

00:19:00.191 --> 00:19:02.897
But if you are trying to use
some assistive technology,

00:19:02.931 --> 00:19:05.680
it's going to be pretty
tricky to use this button.

00:19:06.079 --> 00:19:08.839
And it's going to read it out weirdly
in a screen reader.

00:19:09.039 --> 00:19:11.359
If you use something like
naturally speaking,

00:19:11.720 --> 00:19:14.359
it's going to be hard to identify
a specific button.

00:19:14.519 --> 00:19:15.821
So if there was a spell checker,

00:19:15.846 --> 00:19:18.440
you could avoid these
accessibility problems altogether.

00:19:20.039 --> 00:19:23.643
Something else that you could automatically
do is report readability levels.

00:19:23.839 --> 00:19:26.640
And I think I've seen this
in some SEO plugins.

00:19:26.857 --> 00:19:29.658
But it's also a very valid
thing to do for accessibility

00:19:29.683 --> 00:19:32.160
to make sure that the
text is nice and easy to read.

00:19:32.519 --> 00:19:34.530
And you could have readability levels

00:19:34.887 --> 00:19:37.559
warn the user when they've added text
that's too complicated

00:19:37.559 --> 00:19:40.119
and maybe help them fix the problems
there as well.

00:19:42.880 --> 00:19:46.559
Something else that the standard recommends
is to provide accessible examples.

00:19:46.559 --> 00:19:50.078
So if you work on documentation,
you can do a great deal as well

00:19:50.103 --> 00:19:53.928
about accessibility of your CMS or plugin

00:19:53.952 --> 00:19:56.146
by making sure that all of the examples

00:19:56.171 --> 00:19:59.160
really help the user to
get their accessibility right.

00:19:59.400 --> 00:20:02.366
Sometimes that means the
stuff that maybe gets copy pasted,

00:20:02.391 --> 00:20:06.795
really ensuring that everything
there is perfectly accessible.

00:20:06.839 --> 00:20:09.735
Sometimes it means providing
the right guidelines like, you know,

00:20:09.759 --> 00:20:13.160
if you leave this field empty,
there won't be alternative text.

00:20:13.160 --> 00:20:14.773
So make sure you put something in there

00:20:14.798 --> 00:20:17.640
or explain kind of how
alternative text works.

00:20:17.880 --> 00:20:23.762
So it's really putting in an extra mile and
making sure that the example is accessible

00:20:23.787 --> 00:20:26.104
and really encourages good accessibility.

00:20:27.799 --> 00:20:31.530
So basically a good CMS can
encourage more accessible content

00:20:31.555 --> 00:20:34.200
and help people get
their accessibility right.

00:20:34.799 --> 00:20:36.938
Now I've talked about
the standard quite a bit,

00:20:36.962 --> 00:20:39.035
but I think one of the exciting things

00:20:39.059 --> 00:20:41.718
about authoring tools
that help with accessibility

00:20:41.743 --> 00:20:43.920
is that they can really
help with your process.

00:20:44.680 --> 00:20:48.960
Let's look now at when in the process
authoring tools can help.

00:20:49.200 --> 00:20:52.799
Now process is a bit of a tricky
subject, I think,

00:20:53.119 --> 00:20:56.399
because whoever you talk to,
depending on their organization,

00:20:56.423 --> 00:20:59.228
they will have different ways
of organizing their projects.

00:20:59.253 --> 00:21:02.941
Now this is an example of a process
that your organization might be following

00:21:02.966 --> 00:21:05.440
if it follows the waterfall principles.

00:21:06.440 --> 00:21:09.623
So you might start with some
planning and strategy sessions,

00:21:09.648 --> 00:21:11.794
then do interaction design,
then visual design,

00:21:11.818 --> 00:21:14.119
then development,
then QA, then launch.

00:21:15.119 --> 00:21:18.759
You might have a process that is much
more multidisciplinary.

00:21:19.440 --> 00:21:22.920
So you might have all the disciplines
working together in iterations.

00:21:23.200 --> 00:21:26.839
That could be a thing in sprints or
doing something like scrum.

00:21:28.440 --> 00:21:31.781
Or you might be going back and
forward between these phases,

00:21:31.806 --> 00:21:35.311
like going back from launch to
strategy or to interaction design,

00:21:35.336 --> 00:21:37.599
or sometimes maybe
from QA to design.

00:21:38.640 --> 00:21:41.791
Whatever you're doing, I think
there is a lot to say

00:21:41.816 --> 00:21:44.983
about where authoring tools
fit into the process.

00:21:45.515 --> 00:21:48.219
For instance, if you're working
in planning and strategy,

00:21:48.244 --> 00:21:50.854
you can make a huge difference
by choosing an authoring tool

00:21:50.879 --> 00:21:53.839
that supports accessibility in the ways
that I outlined before.

00:21:54.119 --> 00:21:58.162
So adopting a lot of the principles in ATAG

00:21:58.187 --> 00:22:01.821
and really helping the user
to get their accessibility right

00:22:01.846 --> 00:22:03.202
can really help in the long run.

00:22:03.227 --> 00:22:07.858
Because if that's the case,
then later on in the process,

00:22:07.883 --> 00:22:11.960
it will be much easier for the organization
to create web pages that are accessible.

00:22:13.065 --> 00:22:16.004
In the interaction design phase,
you could spend a great deal

00:22:16.029 --> 00:22:19.960
on how content should be authored
in an accessible manner.

00:22:20.440 --> 00:22:24.162
You could test the authoring process
with people with disabilities

00:22:24.187 --> 00:22:27.519
if user testing is part of your
interaction design discipline.

00:22:28.344 --> 00:22:30.158
If you're doing visual design,

00:22:30.183 --> 00:22:33.316
you could provide guidelines
for customizing color

00:22:33.341 --> 00:22:35.388
so that contrast works well.

00:22:35.555 --> 00:22:40.279
You could work on accessible examples
like large enough touch targets.

00:22:40.839 --> 00:22:43.957
All these sorts of things can
help you in the design phase

00:22:43.982 --> 00:22:48.339
to make sure that anyone who's
authoring web pages later on,

00:22:48.364 --> 00:22:50.680
because you might not be
designing every single web page.

00:22:50.680 --> 00:22:52.680
It might happen in the templating
phase and then

00:22:53.319 --> 00:22:56.680
content people might work with designs
that were created.

00:22:56.880 --> 00:23:00.559
So providing some guidelines there can
really help in the authoring phase.

00:23:01.160 --> 00:23:04.874
When we're talking about development,
you could make a great difference

00:23:04.899 --> 00:23:07.529
by picking a theme
that has accessibility support

00:23:07.553 --> 00:23:09.519
or a plugin with accessibility support.

00:23:09.960 --> 00:23:14.201
Because again, you'll help
people who create web content

00:23:14.225 --> 00:23:17.013
to do that in a more accessible manner,

00:23:17.038 --> 00:23:19.616
or sometimes get a lot
of accessibility for free

00:23:19.641 --> 00:23:23.200
if there's a carousel component or
something that was built accessibly.

00:23:24.303 --> 00:23:28.087
When it comes to QA, you could
embed automated accessibility tests

00:23:28.112 --> 00:23:29.440
in the authoring process.

00:23:29.759 --> 00:23:34.173
So for instance, if someone
creates a new page and presses save,

00:23:34.198 --> 00:23:36.809
that there are some tests
that are running automatically.

00:23:36.834 --> 00:23:41.494
If you have some test automation engineers
in your team, take advantage of them

00:23:41.519 --> 00:23:45.727
and let them help make the
authoring process more valuable as well

00:23:45.751 --> 00:23:47.167
in terms of accessibility.

00:23:48.119 --> 00:23:49.290
And then when you launch,

00:23:49.314 --> 00:23:51.801
you may have something
that is much more accessible

00:23:51.826 --> 00:23:54.817
than if you wouldn't
have done all those things.

00:23:55.559 --> 00:23:57.730
Because many websites are launched

00:23:57.754 --> 00:24:00.559
without much required
for accessibility, sadly.

00:24:01.359 --> 00:24:02.606
That still happens.

00:24:02.640 --> 00:24:06.905
And those websites might find that
they then hire accessibility consultants,

00:24:06.930 --> 00:24:09.480
get a big list of issues
that they'd never thought of.

00:24:10.240 --> 00:24:14.720
And it might take them a lot more time to
work through all of those issues.

00:24:14.745 --> 00:24:16.998
So if you start very much
in the planning phase

00:24:17.023 --> 00:24:19.899
and think about accessibility
in all of these different phases,

00:24:19.923 --> 00:24:22.284
and I know that's not a new thing,

00:24:22.309 --> 00:24:25.240
but I just want to say that that
really makes a big difference.

00:24:25.240 --> 00:24:28.822
And if you think of authoring
in all of these phases,

00:24:28.847 --> 00:24:33.369
that can really help create
much more accessible things by default.

00:24:35.431 --> 00:24:38.439
Now, it may be clear to
you by now that at WAI,

00:24:38.464 --> 00:24:42.720
we find authoring tools are really
important part of web accessibility.

00:24:43.215 --> 00:24:44.240
And to that extent,

00:24:44.265 --> 00:24:48.440
we're doing a number of
things to improve the situation.

00:24:49.680 --> 00:24:53.577
The first thing is, I just
want to mention that

00:24:53.602 --> 00:24:56.708
if the ATAG standard
itself is a bit of a long read,

00:24:56.732 --> 00:25:00.005
there is also the implementing
ATAG 2.0 document

00:25:00.030 --> 00:25:03.653
that has rationale and intent
for each of the success criteria,

00:25:03.678 --> 00:25:05.839
and a bunch of different
practical examples.

00:25:05.839 --> 00:25:09.400
And I've taken some of the examples in
this presentation from there as well.

00:25:09.920 --> 00:25:12.739
It helps to understand ATAG a bit better

00:25:12.764 --> 00:25:16.311
if you get stuck in the main
ATAG document.

00:25:17.415 --> 00:25:19.453
Now, something that I'm
involved with personally

00:25:19.478 --> 00:25:21.720
is something called the WAI Guide Project.

00:25:22.024 --> 00:25:24.131
Now, one thing that we're
creating as part of that

00:25:24.155 --> 00:25:28.206
to help people use the authoring
process that I just outlined,

00:25:28.231 --> 00:25:31.830
like really putting authoring
tools at the front and center

00:25:31.855 --> 00:25:34.319
to help you get your accessibility right.

00:25:35.079 --> 00:25:38.640
We want to help people find tools
that support accessibility.

00:25:38.799 --> 00:25:43.138
So we've created a list of authoring tools
where you can filter by ATAG criteria

00:25:43.163 --> 00:25:45.425
and find tools that support accessibility.

00:25:46.039 --> 00:25:49.512
Now, this is all still dummy data
that you can see here.

00:25:49.920 --> 00:25:50.960
It's not live yet.

00:25:51.880 --> 00:25:55.400
But we are working on getting our
first entries into the list.

00:25:55.400 --> 00:25:59.874
And, you know, if you create a tool
that you think qualifies for this

00:25:59.899 --> 00:26:01.167
and has accessibility support

00:26:01.192 --> 00:26:04.048
and that meets one or more
of the ATAG criteria,

00:26:04.073 --> 00:26:06.652
do get in touch. I'd be
interested to hear from you.

00:26:08.200 --> 00:26:11.885
At the same time, we're also working
on something called the ATAG report tool

00:26:11.910 --> 00:26:15.200
where you can report on ATAG criteria.

00:26:15.559 --> 00:26:18.478
So you can fill in some details

00:26:18.502 --> 00:26:20.351
and then you go to each of the guidelines

00:26:20.376 --> 00:26:22.788
and then you will say
whether it passes or fails

00:26:22.813 --> 00:26:25.859
and you can fill in some
information about each of them.

00:26:26.279 --> 00:26:30.160
Now, this is kind of on
an optional basis.

00:26:30.160 --> 00:26:31.720
So each of these are optional.

00:26:31.720 --> 00:26:33.920
You can fill in the ones that
you want to showcase.

00:26:34.160 --> 00:26:37.846
So if you particularly deal
with one of the criteria well,

00:26:37.871 --> 00:26:40.640
then you fill in those and maybe
leave the others empty.

00:26:41.000 --> 00:26:43.519
Of course, we want to have as many
criteria as possible.

00:26:43.519 --> 00:26:47.079
That will also make it easier for people
to find your tool in our list.

00:26:48.240 --> 00:26:52.039
But yeah, we welcome reports
this way as well.

00:26:52.400 --> 00:26:57.079
In this tool, you are able to create
a report in JSON or HTML.

00:26:57.519 --> 00:26:59.927
And you can also publish that
on your website

00:26:59.951 --> 00:27:01.880
to showcase how well you meet ATAG.

00:27:02.160 --> 00:27:05.596
And ultimately, you would be able to create
a listing in the authoring tools list

00:27:05.621 --> 00:27:06.821
that we're working on.

00:27:07.000 --> 00:27:09.020
At the moment,
there's not that connection yet

00:27:09.045 --> 00:27:11.519
because it's still in its early phases.

00:27:11.519 --> 00:27:16.559
But yeah, very much interested to hearing
your feedback on this tool as well.

00:27:17.314 --> 00:27:21.933
Now, going to conclusions,
what I wanted to share with you today

00:27:21.966 --> 00:27:26.519
is very much that CMSs are
essential for an accessible web.

00:27:26.839 --> 00:27:33.000
It won't surprise you as people who work on
CMSs and plugins and maybe themes even.

00:27:33.599 --> 00:27:37.319
But yeah, your work is very important
for web accessibility.

00:27:37.319 --> 00:27:41.960
I hope this talk gave some more insights
in more ways than it does.

00:27:42.359 --> 00:27:45.539
Now, secondly, I think CMSs
should really help content editors

00:27:45.564 --> 00:27:47.160
get their accessibility right.

00:27:47.440 --> 00:27:50.920
And I hope in this talk I've outlined
a number of ways in which they can.

00:27:51.759 --> 00:27:56.279
So yeah, hopefully we can really see our
CMSs as accessibility assistants.

00:27:57.119 --> 00:27:59.039
And that's the question
I want to leave you with.

00:27:59.039 --> 00:28:02.078
How would you turn your CMS,
your plugin, your theme

00:28:02.103 --> 00:28:04.928
into a better assistant
for web accessibility?

00:28:05.279 --> 00:28:06.880
For now, thanks very much for listening.

00:28:06.880 --> 00:28:10.039
You can find the slides on
talks.hiddedevries.nl.

00:28:10.559 --> 00:28:17.160
It's also going to have all the resources,
links, and video ultimately, I think.

00:28:18.000 --> 00:28:20.720
If you have any questions, feel
free to get in touch.

00:28:20.720 --> 00:28:22.759
It's hidde@w3.org.

00:28:23.279 --> 00:28:25.012
Or you can reach out on Twitter.

00:28:25.037 --> 00:28:28.994
Now I'm going to be showing up in
a live Q&amp;A right after this.

00:28:29.399 --> 00:28:31.494
So with that, I want to
just thank you for listening

00:28:31.519 --> 00:28:34.400
and shout out to the organizers
of WordPress Accessibility Day.

00:28:34.400 --> 00:28:38.390
Thanks so much for putting this event
on and inviting me to speak.

00:28:48.920 --> 00:28:53.000
<v Ahmed>Thank you so much, Hidde, with
that presentation.

00:28:53.480 --> 00:28:56.559
We actually was able to learn
a lot of things

00:28:56.599 --> 00:29:01.000
that are very, very important
to choosing CMSs.

00:29:01.225 --> 00:29:03.000
And we have a bunch of questions.

00:29:03.279 --> 00:29:07.319
So let's just start with the first one
while a few more comes in.

00:29:07.559 --> 00:29:12.599
So the first question we have for you is,
what would be the most important feature

00:29:13.279 --> 00:29:17.039
you must change in Gutenberg to
be completely accessible?

00:29:17.160 --> 00:29:19.626
If you need to correct something,
you could also do that.

00:29:21.880 --> 00:29:24.109
<v Hidde>Yeah, so I'm probably not
the right person to ask

00:29:24.134 --> 00:29:26.920
because I don't work on Gutenberg.

00:29:27.400 --> 00:29:31.273
I think one very interesting presentation
that would get you up to date

00:29:31.298 --> 00:29:37.119
with the latest on Gutenberg accessibility
is by Joe Dolson at the WordPress campus.

00:29:37.559 --> 00:29:39.920
The video of that has recently
been released.

00:29:39.960 --> 00:29:42.276
And I think that will
give you a good overview

00:29:42.301 --> 00:29:45.575
of the stuff that that team is working on,

00:29:45.599 --> 00:29:49.519
sometimes struggling with,
sometimes really massively improving.

00:29:49.759 --> 00:29:54.119
So there's a lot of work happening on
Gutenberg, which I think is great.

00:29:54.160 --> 00:29:59.079
It's hard to make an editor of the future
and also do it accessibly.

00:29:59.079 --> 00:30:00.896
So I admire the effort.

00:30:00.921 --> 00:30:04.160
I think there's lots of great
work happening there.

00:30:04.480 --> 00:30:08.840
But I don't have too much to say about
the actual issues there.

00:30:10.678 --> 00:30:11.751
<v Ahmed>Awesome.

00:30:11.790 --> 00:30:18.582
Next one is your suggestion, if you
know of any good tool for developers

00:30:18.607 --> 00:30:23.400
to test the different levels
of accessibility, A, AA or AAA.

00:30:25.200 --> 00:30:28.119
<v Hidde>Yeah, so those levels, they actually
exist in multiple standards.

00:30:28.200 --> 00:30:32.525
So most people will refer to them
when they look at the WCAG standard

00:30:32.550 --> 00:30:35.599
that has these three levels, A, AA and AAA.

00:30:36.110 --> 00:30:38.031
The ATAG standard does as well.

00:30:38.119 --> 00:30:42.326
Now for the WCAG standard, there's a
bunch of different automated test tools

00:30:42.351 --> 00:30:48.240
that try to interpret the rules that are in
WCAG as test rules and run automatically.

00:30:50.319 --> 00:30:53.519
For ATAG, those don't really exist.

00:30:54.254 --> 00:30:56.775
So at W3C, we have this
project called ACT rules

00:30:56.800 --> 00:30:59.803
where we try to bring
different tool vendors together

00:30:59.827 --> 00:31:03.599
and work on test rules,
harmonize those test rules

00:31:03.599 --> 00:31:06.799
so that every tool kind of interprets
WCAG the same way.

00:31:07.423 --> 00:31:09.646
I think that's an
interesting project to watch

00:31:09.671 --> 00:31:12.920
if you want to know more
about different rules that exist.

00:31:14.359 --> 00:31:16.858
But yeah, you can definitely
test automatically for WCAG

00:31:16.883 --> 00:31:19.405
that is good for
if you're developing a CMS

00:31:19.429 --> 00:31:22.519
because one of the ATAG
guidelines is conform to WCAG.

00:31:23.080 --> 00:31:25.795
So that's, that's good
for the editing experience,

00:31:25.820 --> 00:31:27.788
but it's also good for the output.

00:31:27.813 --> 00:31:31.483
So if you check the page
that is being generated

00:31:31.508 --> 00:31:33.340
or that the editor is working on,

00:31:33.365 --> 00:31:35.356
if you run that through
some automated test tool,

00:31:35.381 --> 00:31:39.319
you might also be able to
prevent some accessibility issues.

00:31:40.823 --> 00:31:44.839
<v Ahmed>Great.
So the next question is one of my favorite.

00:31:45.211 --> 00:31:47.731
And this one asks,

00:31:47.755 --> 00:31:53.431
why are we all focusing on
WCAG and not also on ATAG?

00:31:53.456 --> 00:31:57.920
Is there a bias? Is there a priority
when we're choosing?

00:31:59.871 --> 00:32:01.790
<v Hidde>This is a great question.

00:32:02.123 --> 00:32:04.765
and something we noticed at WAI as well.

00:32:04.790 --> 00:32:09.734
And kind of partly the reason why
I'm now assigned to work on this.

00:32:09.759 --> 00:32:15.484
We would love more people to embrace ATAG
and show the benefits of embracing ATAG

00:32:15.509 --> 00:32:18.865
not just for people who
make CMSs or sell plugins,

00:32:18.890 --> 00:32:20.920
but also for the companies that buy them.

00:32:21.192 --> 00:32:24.968
We feel like there's a unique
selling point to be made

00:32:24.993 --> 00:32:29.311
because so many organizations are
now required by law to be accessible.

00:32:29.336 --> 00:32:31.289
and if your tool can help them,

00:32:31.314 --> 00:32:32.963
you might be able to
charge them more money.

00:32:32.988 --> 00:32:37.000
So we feel like there's a lot of
benefit to looking at ATAG.

00:32:37.279 --> 00:32:40.114
It's not happening, or it
wasn't happening so much.

00:32:40.139 --> 00:32:42.864
We see more uptake in the last year,

00:32:42.888 --> 00:32:44.680
and more people talking about it.

00:32:45.644 --> 00:32:49.455
We heard Susanna talk earlier about
the accessibility of authoring tools

00:32:49.480 --> 00:32:51.226
and we have this, this
conference day today.

00:32:51.251 --> 00:32:54.559
So there's more talk about it.

00:32:55.265 --> 00:32:57.814
and that is great. We see
more people focus on it.

00:32:57.880 --> 00:33:00.911
But I think one of the main reasons
is that WCAG is a standard

00:33:00.936 --> 00:33:03.559
that is embraced by so
many governments worldwide.

00:33:03.559 --> 00:33:08.521
and the one thing that they
put in into legislation often.

00:33:08.990 --> 00:33:13.720
ATAG is not, but it can really help
to, to meet that WCAG legislation.

00:33:13.720 --> 00:33:16.734
So I hope to have showed that
a bit in this talk as well.

00:33:16.767 --> 00:33:18.599
And these things can really play together.

00:33:20.559 --> 00:33:24.289
<v Ahmed>Awesome. Since we talked
about the content management system

00:33:24.313 --> 00:33:26.078
being an accessibility assistant,

00:33:26.103 --> 00:33:28.655
the next few questions
focuses on WordPress.

00:33:28.680 --> 00:33:31.164
So this is my personal
question to you.

00:33:31.772 --> 00:33:35.449
How ready do you think
WordPress is right now

00:33:35.474 --> 00:33:39.559
to serve as an accessibility assistant
among the CMS that are out there?

00:33:41.559 --> 00:33:44.757
<v Hidde>Yeah. So I look at a lot of
different CMSs for my work

00:33:44.782 --> 00:33:47.421
and my work is vendor neutral, so to say.

00:33:47.445 --> 00:33:50.301
So I don't look too much at specifics.

00:33:50.326 --> 00:33:52.711
I do know in WordPress,
there are things like:

00:33:52.735 --> 00:33:56.292
good options for
alternative text for images.

00:33:56.317 --> 00:33:59.887
So there's a clear information
on what you should do there.

00:33:59.912 --> 00:34:01.244
I think that's very helpful.

00:34:02.119 --> 00:34:05.252
there is also something about
color contrast. I remember

00:34:05.277 --> 00:34:10.039
that will show you if you have the wrong
color contrast and help you get it right.

00:34:10.519 --> 00:34:13.591
I think those are great features.

00:34:14.226 --> 00:34:16.112
I think there's a page
structure thing as well.

00:34:16.136 --> 00:34:18.280
So there's a bunch of things in WordPress

00:34:18.280 --> 00:34:21.621
that really can help people
get their accessibility right.

00:34:22.494 --> 00:34:25.676
but also work to do. I think
people of the accessibility team

00:34:25.701 --> 00:34:27.501
and the organizer of this event,

00:34:27.526 --> 00:34:31.599
will be more up to date with the
things that are still being worked on.

00:34:32.880 --> 00:34:35.409
<v Ahmed>Yeah, we can certainly
look towards the future.

00:34:35.433 --> 00:34:40.259
So if you had to rate WordPress
as an accessibility assistant,

00:34:40.284 --> 00:34:43.800
how would you rate it
amongst A, AA and AAA?

00:34:43.800 --> 00:34:47.522
I know it can get controversial, but up to
you, if you want to make any comments?

00:34:48.123 --> 00:34:50.174
<v Hidde>I cannot possibly comment on that

00:34:50.198 --> 00:34:53.433
because we look at
all the different CMSs

00:34:53.458 --> 00:34:56.989
and we want everyone to meet
as many criteria as possible.

00:34:57.014 --> 00:34:59.560
Good thing to mention there is that,

00:34:59.585 --> 00:35:03.694
it's not about meeting all of ATAG
or being completely compliant.

00:35:03.719 --> 00:35:07.800
Just like with WCAG that is pretty hard to
do, and not many organizations do it.

00:35:08.288 --> 00:35:12.185
And they have to by law, but
you know, it's a continuous process

00:35:12.210 --> 00:35:16.295
when one person updates one
image, it could be inaccessible.

00:35:16.320 --> 00:35:20.016
The point is really to meet as
many of these criteria as possible.

00:35:20.041 --> 00:35:23.254
And, you know, every
little bit really helps.

00:35:23.279 --> 00:35:26.100
And we see that a
lot that organizations are doing that.

00:35:26.124 --> 00:35:29.419
And also that CMSs are, are
making small improvements

00:35:29.444 --> 00:35:30.808
and they are all helpful.

00:35:30.833 --> 00:35:35.404
and the end users will be happy
with these improvements, I think,

00:35:36.189 --> 00:35:38.240
<v Ahmed>I must admit it did that.

00:35:38.264 --> 00:35:42.779
Our talk is certainly sparking a little
bit of conversation in the chat feed.

00:35:42.804 --> 00:35:44.942
We're getting a few more
questions as we speak.

00:35:44.967 --> 00:35:49.565
We have time. So the next
question is on Craft CMS

00:35:49.589 --> 00:35:52.434
Is Craft CMS much better than WordPress

00:35:52.458 --> 00:35:56.265
in terms of the accessibility
of the editor? Thoughts.

00:35:57.383 --> 00:36:02.380
<v Hidde>Are you referring to the
W3C choice of CMS?

00:36:02.422 --> 00:36:04.857
<v Ahmed>I suppose so.
That's the question.

00:36:05.679 --> 00:36:09.679
<v Hidde>So I really like to refer to the blog
post that were published about this

00:36:09.679 --> 00:36:14.719
because I had a tiny part in
discussing this internally, of course.

00:36:16.350 --> 00:36:19.040
The main, points are we found

00:36:19.064 --> 00:36:23.436
not many tools meet all
of the criteria that we need.

00:36:23.461 --> 00:36:25.312
And that's a lot of different criteria.

00:36:25.337 --> 00:36:30.090
So we need an accessible CMS. We need
a CMS that supports internationalization

00:36:30.115 --> 00:36:31.971
because we work with the global community.

00:36:33.280 --> 00:36:38.097
bunch of different things basically that
we've decided our CMS choice based on

00:36:38.407 --> 00:36:40.519
accessibility was one of them.

00:36:40.840 --> 00:36:44.982
And in my work, I really tried to convince
other organizations to do what we did,

00:36:45.173 --> 00:36:47.010
make accessibility part of that choice

00:36:47.034 --> 00:36:49.473
because it's going to
help you in the process.

00:36:49.498 --> 00:36:50.960
Like I showed in the slides.

00:36:51.409 --> 00:36:56.599
They did that. So the vendor
that we hired for the new website,

00:36:56.624 --> 00:37:01.780
they looked at these different aspects
and also an accessibility.

00:37:02.153 --> 00:37:07.199
and they looked at how
they feel it is going to improve.

00:37:07.559 --> 00:37:11.400
And that is, you know, that's a different,
difficult thing to assess

00:37:11.840 --> 00:37:14.039
because, you know, you cannot
look into the future.

00:37:15.263 --> 00:37:20.145
But yeah, it seems like for them
that the Craft CMS had more commitment,

00:37:20.170 --> 00:37:22.664
maybe also from the top

00:37:22.689 --> 00:37:25.728
to make that accessibility
features better.

00:37:27.490 --> 00:37:30.680
but yeah, maybe WordPress will be a
better choice for other organizations.

00:37:30.705 --> 00:37:33.051
It's really tricky to say,

00:37:33.076 --> 00:37:35.909
and I can't comment in
too much detail about that.

00:37:36.440 --> 00:37:38.373
<v Ahmed>So that's fair enough, Hidde.

00:37:38.397 --> 00:37:40.960
I think I can understand
where you're coming from.

00:37:41.320 --> 00:37:44.907
So such forum where we discuss

00:37:44.932 --> 00:37:49.439
and we try to assess CMSs
if they're accessibility ready.

00:37:49.680 --> 00:37:52.974
So such questions are quite
realistic, I suppose.

00:37:52.999 --> 00:37:56.806
But then again, I request you to
go through our website

00:37:56.831 --> 00:37:58.280
and answer the question.

00:37:58.280 --> 00:38:00.559
I'm sure you will be given
the link later.

00:38:00.719 --> 00:38:05.866
Also viewers, we've also shared the
slides to the presentation by Hidde.

00:38:05.891 --> 00:38:07.760
Before I can ask you
the last question.

00:38:07.760 --> 00:38:11.889
So the last one says,
have you tried to use ACF

00:38:11.914 --> 00:38:17.175
and a headless front end as editor
to get accessibility content creation?

00:38:20.039 --> 00:38:23.277
<v Hidde>Yes, not in
my capacity at the W3C,

00:38:23.302 --> 00:38:26.719
but I do have some
personal experience with that.

00:38:28.261 --> 00:38:30.393
something in general,
you can say about—

00:38:32.241 --> 00:38:34.853
So ACF is advanced
custom field, right?

00:38:34.878 --> 00:38:36.440
So you define your own fields.

00:38:37.832 --> 00:38:39.967
and what's interesting about that

00:38:39.992 --> 00:38:43.970
is that you could have just
strings of text that people put in

00:38:44.327 --> 00:38:47.039
and then you can invent
your own markup around that.

00:38:47.039 --> 00:38:49.599
So you control all of the accessibility.

00:38:50.274 --> 00:38:52.901
You could do it badly and you
could do it greatly, right?

00:38:52.926 --> 00:38:58.440
So like I mentioned, some CMSs don't
have the option to add captions to a video.

00:38:59.119 --> 00:39:03.880
If you create your own fields, then
you can create a field for captions.

00:39:03.880 --> 00:39:06.453
So you can really control that yourself

00:39:06.478 --> 00:39:10.489
and make it more of an
accessibility assistant in a way as well,

00:39:10.513 --> 00:39:13.935
because you can explain
why they need captions.

00:39:13.960 --> 00:39:16.862
Do it in a way that is
the perfect tone of voice

00:39:16.887 --> 00:39:20.559
and that will inspire people to do it
rather than make them annoyed.

00:39:20.614 --> 00:39:22.285
Because I saw someone asked like,

00:39:22.309 --> 00:39:26.311
you know, how can we avoid
that people choose a different CMS

00:39:26.336 --> 00:39:28.639
if we confront them with
accessibility too much.

00:39:29.021 --> 00:39:32.039
So yeah, if we have
that positive tone of voice,

00:39:32.064 --> 00:39:35.055
and that's something you can really
control if you define your own fields.

00:39:35.436 --> 00:39:40.159
So yeah, that's a… if you are
an integrator with WordPress,

00:39:40.159 --> 00:39:43.404
then I think that makes a lot of sense
to try and define your own fields

00:39:43.429 --> 00:39:48.659
and get full control over what these
fields look like and what they say.

00:39:50.119 --> 00:39:52.694
<v Ahmed>Thank you so much, Hidde, with your time,

00:39:52.719 --> 00:39:55.159
your effort and patience
with the questions.

00:39:55.400 --> 00:39:59.380
Before we can wrap up, I would like
to ask you one personal question.

00:39:59.753 --> 00:40:05.347
How would you like the stakeholders
out there who can make a difference

00:40:05.372 --> 00:40:08.315
to initiatives such as WordPress
Accessibility Day?

00:40:08.360 --> 00:40:10.440
We know this is only happening
for the first time.

00:40:10.838 --> 00:40:17.536
If you had the platform, if you had a
voice, what would your message be out there

00:40:17.561 --> 00:40:19.480
for the people who can make the difference?

00:40:20.780 --> 00:40:22.883
<v Hidde>The difference in choosing...

00:40:22.908 --> 00:40:27.119
<v Ahmed>In making such initiatives
better and more accessible.

00:40:29.118 --> 00:40:31.119
<v Hidde>Like the today's event or...

00:40:31.119 --> 00:40:32.255
<v Ahmed>Today's event, yep.

00:40:32.280 --> 00:40:33.719
Yes, Hidde, thank you.

00:40:35.094 --> 00:40:37.159
<v Hidde>Ah, that's a tricky one.
I don't know.

00:40:37.159 --> 00:40:41.800
I mean, there's captions.
So that's, that's good.

00:40:42.255 --> 00:40:44.383
I don't know. I haven't
looked too much

00:40:44.408 --> 00:40:48.039
into the accessibility
aspects of today's event.

00:40:49.519 --> 00:40:51.840
<v Ahmed>I'm sure we will
have your support for the future.

00:40:51.840 --> 00:40:55.280
So on that note, we come
to the end of this session.

00:40:55.854 --> 00:40:58.574
"Your CMS is an accessibility
assistant."

00:40:58.599 --> 00:41:01.074
I want to personally thank
Hidde for being patient enough

00:41:01.107 --> 00:41:02.622
and answering all the questions.

00:41:02.960 --> 00:41:08.118
Also I want to give a huge shout out to
Harish who has been acting as the moderator

00:41:08.143 --> 00:41:11.159
for this session, posting
the questions on our site.

00:41:11.440 --> 00:41:13.556
Also, I would like to give a huge shout out

00:41:13.597 --> 00:41:16.239
to the session manager,
Stefano, working in the background.

00:41:16.516 --> 00:41:19.656
So I also would like to
thank everyone for attending,

00:41:19.681 --> 00:41:21.415
with Hidde and myself.

00:41:21.440 --> 00:41:27.538
You can continue the conversation
using hashtag WPAD, hashtag WPAD2020

00:41:27.911 --> 00:41:30.519
at the rate
of WP accessibility.

00:41:30.880 --> 00:41:32.854
Don't forget to attend the next talk:

00:41:32.879 --> 00:41:35.365
If it's true, it ain't bragging.

00:41:35.400 --> 00:41:39.354
Choosing a CMS for accessibility
with Mitchell Evan and myself,

00:41:39.379 --> 00:41:42.599
right at 9am UTC here in the same time.

00:41:43.039 --> 00:41:45.760
Until that happens, see you right
here after the break.

00:41:46.038 --> 00:41:47.212
Thank you so much, Hidde.

00:41:47.360 --> 00:41:48.420
Bye bye.

00:41:49.047 --> 00:41:50.460
<v Hidde>Thanks so much for having me.